Alright, but how exactly does "A Redundant Deterministic Verification of Large Language Models" benefit users / applicatons? Why do they need it?

we need the miners to prove they are running the right model, and then we send inference requests based off tier. higher tiers get multipliers on their score for challenge and inference success rate. 

Instead of relying on a black box to evaluate in lossy terms, we can have miners prove they are running a particular model, leading to better quality control of the outputs. The important thing to understand about Bittensor is that it's not like hashrate mining.  Once you have gotten the infrastructure software (Bittensor) installed, the miner or validator codebase is going to be different depending on which subnet(s) you're working in.  There is a very general checklist for preparing to mine or validate here: https://docs.bittensor.com/subnets/checklist-for-validating-mining but it does not contain step-by-step instructions for any particular model or version of node software, which will be subnet-specific.

You can explore the different subnets through the channels or the new "Subnet Pages" page in the documentation site, here: https://docs.bittensor.com/subnet-pages/ -- note that this is automatically updated from data posted to GitHub, but it does depend on the subnet owners actually updating that.  So if you have any questions about whether the information is up to date, I always recommend that you check the pinned posts in the subnet's channel.

Note that because the code is different in each subnet, and trying to accomplish something different, it means that there is not really going to be an easy way for us to recommend subnets for newcomers, or for specific computer specifications, etc.  It'll be up to you to figure out which one(s) best match your equipment, resources, and skill level, if you are interested in exploring further. : )

"This has already been used to blacklist keys we understand"

I would like to retract this statement since I do not have any direct proof of blacklisting. 
However, the design itself needs to be rethought. I am willing to work with all parties here to find a better solution.

I appreciate you bringing this to our attention on Friday at 10PM. We will spend this weekend rebuilding the challenge api, and will open source the result. I hope this will enable other subnets to use the challenge api as well.

To be clear, the challenge api is used as the dataset in SN4. The purpose of this api is to have a private input that is resistant to lookup attacks. 

We have been facing ddos attacks on the challenge api, and started using the signed hotkey of the verifiers for authentication to mitigate these attacks. These verifier hotkeys are fetched from the metagraph regularly. 

The challenge api  **HAS NEVER** been used to blacklist any verifier keys, nor has it ever been used to manipulate the incentive in any way.
